            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17820220-45-person545">
                  James
                   Day
               <interp inst="t17820220-45-person545" type="surname" value="Day"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17820220-45-person545" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17820220-45-person545" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , the prosecutor, deposed, he lost his buckles on the 14th of February, he went the over night to the prisoner's house, in <placeName id="t17820220-45-crimeloc216">New court, Saffron-hill</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17820220-45-crimeloc216" type="placeName" value="New court, Saffron-hill"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17820220-45-crimeloc216" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17820220-45-off214 t17820220-45-crimeloc216"></join>; I went there with a young woman, I slept there, but not with the prisoner; she never quitted the room till day-light, when she went but with an intent, as she said, to fetch purl in half an hour I missed my buckles; the prisoner was found at ten at night in liquor; my buckles were left in my shoes and knees of my breeches, on the bed side, the other girl did not go out of the room, after I went to bed, I found her at ten o'clock, on Thursday night, the 14th, at the Magpye, on Saffron-hill, much in liquor; I found the buckles the next morning at Mr. Pearson's, the corner of Stonecutter's-street, a pawnbroker.</p>


               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17820220-45-person546">
                  Lawrence
                   Pearson
               <interp inst="t17820220-45-person546" type="surname" value="Pearson"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17820220-45-person546" type="given" value="Lawrence"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17820220-45-person546" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             a pawnbroker deposed, he took in the buckles of the prisoner in the morning, and lent sixteen-shillings on them, (and produced them.)</p>
               <p>The prosecutor deposed to the shoe-buckles; and knee-buckles.</p>
               <p>PRISONER's DEFENCE.</p>
               <p>That the girl's mother gave her the buckles to pledge, but they took me, and sent her about her business.</p>


